  "prompt": "What are your favourite Bob Dylan lyrics?",
  "response": "Bob Dylan is known for his profound and poetic lyrics, and it's tough to pick favorites, but here are a few lines that stand out for their depth and impact:\n\n1. **From \"Blowin' in the Wind\":**\n   ```\n   How many roads must a man walk down\n   Before you call him a man?\n   ```\n   These lines are powerful in their simplicity and open-endedness, prompting reflection on the nature of experience and maturity.\n\n2. **From \"The Times They Are a-Changin'\":**\n   ```\n   Come senators, congressmen\n   Please heed the call\n   Don't stand in the doorway\n   Don't block up the hall\n   ```\n   This is a call to action and a warning to those in power, reflecting Dylan's engagement with social and political issues.\n\n3. **From \"Like a Rolling Stone\":**\n   ```\n   How does it feel\n   To be on your own\n   With no direction home\n   Like a complete unknown\n   Like a rolling stone?\n   ```\n   These lyrics capture a sense of existential drift and vulnerability, resonating with anyone who has felt lost or directionless.\n\n4. **From \"Tangled Up in Blue\":**\n   ```\n   I was working for a while on a fishing boat\n   Right outside of Delacroix\n   But all the while I was alone\n   The past was close behind\n   I seen a lot of women\n   But she never escaped my mind, and I just grew\n   Tangled up in blue\n   ```\n   This song is known for its narrative depth and the way it weaves personal history with emotional reflection.\n\n5. **From \"Forever Young\":**\n   ```\n   May your hands always be busy\n   May your feet always be swift\n   May you have a strong foundation\n   When the winds of changes shift\n   ```\n   These lines offer a heartfelt wish for resilience and adaptability, making it a timeless message for anyone at any age.\n\nThese are just a few examples, but Dylan's catalog is vast and filled with many more gems that continue to inspire and provoke thought.",
